         <abstract>
            <p>The general relief provisions (Section 722) are of great importance. Enacted especially to give relief to corporations whose 1936-1939 earnings provided an inadequate base, the law provides for ascertaining the degree of abnormality and correcting the tax. Administration is going to be difficult, and many fear failure. Yet the need for quick and final action is indicated by the approximately 30,000 applications that have been filed. The Bureau of Internal Revenue's approach to its task promises an equitable and expeditious administration.</p>
